for designing an accessible and affordable water purification system. In an online chat with the press and public, Eshani recalled, “On a trip to India a few summers ago, I noticed the grotesque deformities resulting from water contamination in the slums of my home state. When I asked my relatives why so many people were thus affected, they told me that such maladies were commonplace due to limited access to water filters. Market research revealed that commercial water filters are inaccessible to those who need them most due to tradeoffs between cost and effectiveness. Thanks, everyone! [Chit Chat Thursday, March 18] Moong Dal Khasta Kachori There are multiple variations of Khasta (Crispy) Kachori, my favourite is the one with Moong Dal (Mung bean lentil) and Matar (peas) filling. The Moong dal is soaked, ground into a coarse powder, then cooked with spices to give it an extra kick. Sorry vegans, the crispy texture of the crust is because of ghee, I'll keep working on it. This is one of the oldest extant recipes invented by the Marwari traders (Marwar is \"the South West region\", a part of the state of Rajasthan in India). The name of the place comes from the Sanskrit for 'desert area'. The traders from this region would travel for days across many miles and the needed food that would not spoil in the heat. Their answer was Kachori.. a dal filled ball of dough fried in oil to preserve it. The Marwari were predominately vegetarians who kept to their principles even on these long trips so they found it necessary to pack enough little vegetarian delicacies like these to survive till there and back again. As a fellow nomad, I've always agreed with the Marwari that the travelled life is the life best lived, AND that one should never be without Kachori. In college, I would eat them for breakfast every day till I ran out of money. Then I'd take up tutoring or something to get more money because one cannot be expected to live without Khasta in life \uD83D\uDE09 Each plate comes with two Kachoris, mint chutney, and tamarind chutney. The price of each plate is $12. 17:02:07","updated":"2022-01-06 20:08:38","type":"photo","message":"[Meal Announcement, Tuesday, March 23] Shahi Paneer with Maa Choleyan di daal, Basmati Rice, Naan (optional) Shahi Paneer literally translates to “Royal Cottage Cheese”. The word Shahi comes from the title given to the Mughal Kings who were referred to as “Shahansha” or \"Shah\", like the 'Shah' of Iran. The gravy (or 'sauce' as you say here) that makes it Shahi paneer is yogurt based and made with almonds, cashews, saffron, cardamom, and char magaz (which I'll be grinding in-house, see below). Saffron and Cardamom give this dish a powerfully aromatic flavour and Paneer as a protein adds a nice tender texture. When we were growing up, paneer, in general, was only for special occasions, but Shahi Paneer. It was reserved for the rarest like a birthday or an exceptionally good report card. (Yes, we had to share!) \uD83D\uDE04 \uD83D\uDE04  Char Magaz is a mixture of ground mixture of nuts* and seeds* whose composition probably varies by region. I'm certain that each part of the country is convinced that theirs is the correct one, but sadly they are all mistaken except for us Punjabis. \uD83D\uDE1B It's considered 'cooling' by Ayurvedic practitioners and is reported to cure a long list of ailments. While I cannot guarantee that Mom's Char Magaz will cure you of 'nervine weakness', I can say that it hits the spot when mixed with Shahi Paneer gravy! \uD83D\uDE1B  *allergy warning Maa Choleyan Di Daal is made with a combination of equal parts split Urad Daal (black lentils) and Chana Daal (split chickpeas). The name Maa Choleyan Di Daal means mother’s chickpeas & lentils. This is my second favourite lentil recipe after Maa Ki Daal. This lentil dish is common in our household, mata-rani (my mother) makes it at least once a week if not more. You can also find it pretty regularly at Gurudwaras, which are like temples or synagogues or church for Sikhs. I have not been to Gurudwara since Covid hit the U.S. and I miss it very much. \uD83D\uDE14 The music is relaxing and there's always food afterwards. People of all faiths (or no faith at all) are always welcome at Gurudwara. I'd love to see you all there when this is over! \uD83D\uDE03 My mother’s version of Maa Choleyan Di Daal includes a little onion, some garlic, heeng (asafoetida), ginger tadka (tempering), and kasoori methi (dried methi leaves) for fragrance. As always, the whole plate is served with a generous helping of the best long-grain basmati rice I can find. The price of each plate is $15 and I accept Zelle. I’m selling the naan as an add-on at $3 for two pieces. Please reply here with the number of plates you would like and the number of naans and I'll send you a direct message with details for payment and pickup (masks required). \uD83D\uDE03   I'll be able to cook for up to 12 people. We were one the first ones to get to the check in counter and it barely took 5-10 mins. Was pleasantly surprised by the service by Air India, they were very nice and helpful. Just before and hour or two before landing in Delhi, one aged parent who was traveling alone fainted but was given very good care by the air host and the hostess who quickly reached out to two of the doctors on board and glad things got into control! I was surprised, we were not given the immigration forms to be filled in the flight itself, wish they would have reminded us as I spent quite some time filling it after reaching the immigration counter! \uD83E\uDD26‍♂️ Not sure why, but we are not asked for any hard copies of the negative test results of the self declaration, I took 5 copies! \uD83E\uDD26‍♂️ personally I don’t feel the need for packing food as Air India provided food as it normally does. Customs too was seamless, no issues at all. The only difficult part was transferring the luggage to domestic departures and getting the screening done, the transit time was not adequate enough, luckily the security let us through because of the connecting domestic flight, else would have surely missed the flight with two kids! The connecting transit flight was rescheduled in the morning and the seat selections were overridden, all the passengers with small kids had to request co-passengers to adjust and reshuffle! We missed one baggage in Hyderabad but we were promised to get it delivered by tomorrow as it was misplaced in the last minute in Delhi itself. My suggestion is if you travel as a family try to get direct flights instead of the transit ones. Mixing international and domestic flights did not sound fair as domestic flights did not seem to have this stringent rule of RT-PCR negative report!! Feel free to ask me any specific questions! I was well prepared for the trip because of this forum and very thankful for everyone! The “living” village was an attraction in Hollywood, where Seminole artisans could sell their arts and crafts to tourists. These included patchwork clothing, dolls, and baskets like the one Mary Motlow is weaving out of palmetto leaves in the picture below. \nSome families chose to live in the village seasonally. Dorothy Osceola Tommie and her child Clinton were likely among those families who counted on cultural tourism for income. Visitors paid admission to see the village and to watch wildlife shows, especially alligator wrestling. The Okalee Indian Village gave tourists a taste of the Everglades and taught them about Seminole history and culture.\n(\uD83D\uDCF7: 2009.34.1633) #archives #seminolehistory A visually stunning hand-painted animation, it's a love story set against the bustling city of Bombay, between a young flower seller Kamala and an orphaned refugee, Salim. Flora & Ulysses, directed by IFFLA alum Lena Khan (The Tiger Hunter) is the emotional, hopeful and super-fun journey of the unlikely friendship between a young cynical girl dealing with her parents' separation, and a squirrel with superpowers she finds! Now streaming on Disney+ and Hotstar. The series #BombayBegums, directed by IFFLA alums #AlankritaShrivastava (Lipstick Under My Burkha) and #BornilaChatterjee ( The Hungry) follows five different women from different socioeconomic backgrounds in Mumbai as they try to overcome their daily struggles, achieve their dreams, and stand up to those who are silently complicit with perpetrators of sexual harassment. Basmati Rice and Vegan Naan (optional) Punjabi moms and Aaloo Gobhi share a deep connection. It's not just the subplot from Bend it Like Beckham (really though), it's a real-life point of motherly pride that must be refined and perfected. Moms share their versions of Aaloo Gobhi with their friends and relatives (that they like), but it doesn't matter because each friend or relative is self-assured that their own rendition is the best one. Well, Mata-Rani has given me her recipe! Not that it matters, of course. My version is better. \uD83D\uDE0B (It's the peas!) Punjabi Choley a.k.a (a.k.a. chana masala) is Delhi‘s one of the most popular street foods. It is a curry made with white chickpeas, garlic, ginger, tomatoes, and tamarind to liven up the chickpeas This used to be one of the weekend dishes at home as it takes longer to cook and Mata-Rani (my mother) liked to spend time to get it right. She kept and used her own homemade Chana masala spices for this recipe which is a mix of cardamom, cloves, cumin seeds, fennel seeds, and dry pomegranate seeds. This Choley, in her opinion, is too good to leave in the hands of store-bought curry powders The price of each plate is $15 and I accept Zelle. I’m selling the naan as an add-on at $3 for two pieces. When W...","message":"\"WEBINAR ALERT\" *Topic:- Celebrating the 50th anniversary of Bangladesh independence. *DATE and TIME:- Mar 24, 2021. 03:00 PM in London / 9:00 pm BANGLADESH/ 8:30 pm INDIA. *Description:- Celebrating the 50th anniversary of Bangladesh independence, with NLTV and the Bangabandhu Writer and Journalist Association UK. In the 1970 East Pakistan general election, its largest political party the Awami League won a clear majority for national seats as well as the provincial assembly. When West Pakistan's military leadership refused to hand over power to the democratically elected government, a struggle for independence started. On 7 March 1971 Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, leader of the Awami League, gave his famous speech where he called for a non-cooperation movement. But draconian actions and the commencement of Operation Searchlight signaled the Army was not ready for a peaceful transfer of political power. After support from the Indian army, East Pakistan secured its independence as Bangladesh after Pakistan surrendered on 16 December 1971. The victory is widely seen as India's greatest military feat. *Speakers:- - Dr Murad Hassan MP, Honorable State Minister, Ministry of Information, Bangladesh - Tahir Aslam Gora, Broadcaster and CEO, In the 1970 East Pakistan general election, its largest political party the Awami League won a clear majority for national seats as well as the provincial assembly. When West Pakistan's military leadership refused to hand over power to the democratically elected government, a struggle for independence started. On 7 March 1971 Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, leader of the Awami League, gave his famous speech where he called for a non-cooperation movement. But draconian actions and the commencement of Operation Searchlight signaled the Army was not ready for a peaceful transfer of political power. After support from the Indian army, East Pakistan secured its independence as Bangladesh after Pakistan surrendered on 16 December 1971. The victory is widely seen as India's greatest military feat. *Speakers:- - Dr Murad Hassan MP, Honorable State Minister, Ministry of Information, Bangladesh - Tahir Aslam Gora, Broadcaster and CEO,
